184
20:35.310 --> 20:43.320
but that's just an illusion. Remember that scalar float
freely through tensor products, so there's really no sense
in which alpha and beta

185
20:43.320 --> 20:47.100
are associated with the first qubit.

186
20:47.100 --> 20:55.980
All we've really done
here is to use parentheses in accordance with the
multilinearity of tensor products.

187
20:55.980 --> 21:05.310
Anyway, that's the form that we need to see what the measurement does, and we can see one
interesting thing right away

188
21:05.310 --> 21:10.890
and that is that the probabilities of the four possible measurement outcomes are always uniform.

189
21:10.890 --> 21:17.040
The probability to measure each
pair of measurement outcomes is one quarter, so, in particular,

190
21:17.040 --> 21:21.540
there's no dependence
whatsoever on alpha and beta.

191
21:21.540 --> 21:29.460
We can see that in each case by computing the Euclidean norm squared of
whatever vector is tensored to the standard basis
vector that we isolated,

192
21:29.460 --> 21:36.150
and in each case we have a one quarter which we get by squaring one half times the absolute value squared of alpha

193
21:36.150 --> 21:44.070
plus the absolute value
squared of beta, which is one, and so we get one quarter in each case.

194
21:44.070 --> 21:52.860
It's quite important in
fact that the probabilities of these different outcomes don't depend in any way on the qubit that
Alice wants to transmit.

195
21:52.860 --> 22:02.250
We couldn't have that an arbitrary state comes in up here and comes out down here and yet a measurement revealed
information about that state.

196
22:02.250 --> 22:11.910
If you wanna gain information about an arbitrary quantum state, you're gonna have to disturb
that state in general.

197
22:11.910 --> 22:17.940
Here's a table that describes not only the probabilities
of the different outcomes, but also the state of
the three Qubits together

198
22:17.940 --> 22:22.260
conditioned on each possible
measurement outcome.

199
22:22.260 --> 22:28.380
We get this by normalizing the vectors tensored to the different
standard basis states, but that's easy in this case,

200
22:28.380 --> 22:34.020
we just eliminate the factor of one half to get a unit vector.

201
22:34.020 --> 22:41.760
So, what we have immediately
after Alice measures is that Alice has two uniform
random bits and that's it.

202
22:41.760 --> 22:50.790
In particular, she no longer
has the original state and she doesn't have any
information about it, she just has random bits.

203
22:50.790 --> 22:57.150
Bob's state now does
depend on alpha and beta as well as on the measurement outcomes.

204
22:57.150 --> 23:03.780
If we imagine momentarily
that Alice hasn't yet sent the measurement outcomes
so that Bob doesn't know what the measurement outcomes are,

205
23:03.780 --> 23:09.270
then he wouldn't be able
to gain any information about alpha and beta
from measuring his qubit.

206
23:09.270 --> 23:16.380
These four possibilities
that we have right here are sufficiently scrambled to ensure that no information
about alpha and beta

207
23:16.380 --> 23:25.920
could ever be gained
through a measurement. That has to be true at an intuitive level because otherwise we'd have
faster than light communication.

208
23:25.920 --> 23:33.750
Alice certainly can't
transmit information to Bob without sending anything at all, but of course Alice does
send the measurement outcomes

209
23:33.750 --> 23:41.010
to Bob, so let's expand the table to see what happens when
Bob performs his operations.

210
23:41.010 --> 23:48.270
In this column right here, we have the different operations that Bob effectively performs for each of the possible
outcomes of the measurements

211
23:48.270 --> 23:56.250
like we observed before,
and if we go one by one and we apply that
operation to Bob's qubit, which is the first one, B,

212
23:56.250 --> 24:05.280
we see that we get the same
outcome in all four cases and that outcome is the original state.

213
24:05.280 --> 24:11.940
So, the original state of the qubit Q has been successfully teleported into B.

214
24:11.940 --> 24:20.220
If Bob wants to rename his qubit and call it Q at this point, he's certainly welcome to do that, but the point is that now
he holds the original state

215
24:20.220 --> 24:25.950
that Alice had and of course by necessity, Alice doesn't have it anymore.

216
24:25.950 --> 24:32.490
Notice also that the e-bit
has effectively been burned up through this process,
teleportation has a cost

217
24:32.490 --> 24:40.800
and the cost is one e-bit and two classical bits of communication, and when the protocol is
over, the e-bit is gone.

218
24:40.800 --> 24:47.610
We've now established that
the teleportation protocol works correctly under the assumption that the top qubit is in a quantum state

219
24:47.610 --> 24:53.280
of the form alpha times cat
zero plus beta times cat one.

220
24:53.280 --> 24:59.760
But what happens if the
top qubit is entangled with some other system such as
one of our additional Qubits

221
24:59.760 --> 25:06.150
as we have here on the screen? We might wish to use teleportation
under such circumstances.

222
25:06.150 --> 25:12.420
Maybe Alice and Bob actually
plan to perform teleportation 100 times so that Alice can transmit

223
25:12.420 --> 25:17.670
some 100 qubit quantum register
to Bob, one qubit at a time.

224
25:17.670 --> 25:25.500
Or maybe these additional
Qubits aren't even in Alice's possession at all
and somebody else has them, maybe Alice doesn't even
know that they exist.

225
25:25.500 --> 25:32.850
The question is, does
teleportation still work even though the qubit being teleported is entangled with another system?

226
25:32.850 --> 25:39.510
Here, the state of the qubit Q together with the additional
system that we're considering is expressed as you can see right up here

227
25:39.510 --> 25:46.950
where gamma zero and
gamma one are unit vectors representing quantum states
of this additional system.

228
25:46.950 --> 25:51.600
We can always write an arbitrary state of the combined system in this way.

229
25:51.600 --> 25:59.760
We don't actually even
need alpha and beta here, but if we include them,
then we can take gamma zero and gamma one to be unit vectors

230
25:59.760 --> 26:04.950
and that'll make the
connection to the simpler case we've already considered more transparent.

